---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between an index fund and an ETF?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "An index fund is a mutual fund that tracks a specific market index and is priced once at the end of the trading day. An ETF (Exchange Traded Fund) also tracks an index but trades on an exchange throughout the day like a regular stock. While both offer similar underlying exposure, the trading mechanics differ. ETFs offer intra-day liquidity, meaning you can buy or sell them at the current market price at any time during trading hours. Mutual funds, however, only execute trades at the Net Asset Value (NAV) calculated after the market closes, which can be preferable for investors who want to avoid the temptation to day trade."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why are index funds considered a good investment?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "They offer broad market diversification, historically strong long-term returns, and very low expense ratios compared to actively managed funds, making them an ideal core holding for most investors. By owning a tiny fraction of hundreds or thousands of companies, you eliminate the risk of a single company's bankruptcy destroying your portfolio. Over decades of data, passive index funds have consistently outperformed the vast majority of active fund managers, largely due to their incredibly low fees. This makes them the ultimate 'set it and forget it' investment for wealth accumulation."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Do index funds pay dividends?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, if the underlying stocks in the index pay dividends, the index fund will collect those and distribute them to shareholders, typically on a quarterly basis. The yield of an index fund is simply the weighted average yield of all its underlying holdings, minus the fund's expense ratio. Investors can choose to receive these dividends in cash to fund their living expenses or automatically reinvest them to buy more shares of the fund, which accelerates the power of compound interest over time and maximizes total return."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I lose money in an index fund?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, index funds track the market, so if the overall stock market declines, the value of your index fund will also decline. They carry market risk but eliminate individual company risk. It is completely normal for broad market indexes to experience pullbacks of 10% or more regularly, and occasionally severe bear markets with drawdowns of 30% to 50%. However, history shows that the broader market has always eventually recovered and gone on to make new all-time highs. Therefore, the key to success with index funds is maintaining a long-term perspective and not panic-selling during temporary downturns."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How many index funds do I need?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Many experts suggest a simple 2 or 3-fund portfolio is enough for most investors: a total US stock market fund, a total international stock market fund, and a total bond market fund. This provides complete global diversification. By holding these three low-cost funds, you gain exposure to thousands of companies across the globe and thousands of bonds, perfectly balancing growth and stability. Adding more funds often just creates overlapping holdings and unnecessary complexity without necessarily improving the risk-adjusted returns of your portfolio. Simplicity is often the ultimate sophistication in investing."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "Top Index Funds and ETFs: Comprehensive Guide & Rankings",
      "description": "Looking to build a lazy portfolio? We analyze the top index funds and ETFs on the market. Find out which funds offer the best exposure for the lowest cost.",
      "datePublished": "2026-03-15",
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Research",
        "logo": {
          "@type": "ImageObject",
          "url": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/favicon.ico"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
};

